---

<Layout
  title="Wide Plank Hardwood Flooring in Houston: A Practical Guide | Jamail Hardwoods"
  description="Everything Houston homeowners should know about wide plank hardwood flooring — why it's popular, what widths actually work in our humidity, costs, and real-room examples."
>
  <Header />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Wide Plank Hardwood Flooring in Houston: A Practical Guide",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Joey Jamail" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Jamail Hardwoods", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://jamailfloors.com/images/jamail-logo-hardwoods-transparent-logo.webp" } },
    "datePublished": "2026-05-18",
    "dateModified": "2026-05-18",
    "image": "https://jamailfloors.com/images/Hardwood Flooring Houston Jamail Hardwoods.jpg",
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://jamailfloors.com/blog/wide-plank-hardwood-flooring-houston" }
  })}></script>

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-linear-to-b from-brand-sand/60 via-brand-ivory to-white pointer-events-none"></div>
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-16 pb-10 max-w-3xl">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-xs text-brand-ink/60 mb-4">
        <a href="/blog" class="text-brand-brass hover:underline">← Blog</a>
        <span class="opacity-50">·</span>
        <span class="font-semibold text-brand-brass uppercase tracking-wider">Materials</span>
        <span class="opacity-50">·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">Wide Plank Hardwood Flooring in Houston: A Practical Guide</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>Wide plank hardwood is the look most Houston homeowners want when they renovate today — long, calm, designer-magazine floors with fewer seams and a more refined feel underfoot. But "wide plank" means different things to different installers, and not every width works in Houston's humidity. Here's the honest version.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">If you want our recommendation up front: <strong>7" to 9" engineered European white oak is the sweet spot</strong> for Houston homes. It's wide enough to look modern, narrow enough to handle our climate without cupping, and broadly available from premium European mills.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What "wide plank" actually means</h2>
    <p>There's no industry standard, but in 2026 most installers use these rough categories:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>2.25"–3" — Strip flooring.</strong> Traditional, narrow, very busy look. Not "wide plank."</li>
      <li><strong>3"–5" — Standard plank.</strong> What most older homes have. Fine but visually busy.</li>
      <li><strong>5"–7" — Wide plank (entry-level).</strong> Where the modern wide-plank look starts.</li>
      <li><strong>7"–9" — Wide plank (premium).</strong> The current designer-favorite range. Calm, modern, refined.</li>
      <li><strong>9"–12"+ — Extra-wide plank.</strong> Dramatic, expensive, harder to install well, more prone to humidity issues.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Why wide plank works visually</h2>
    <p>Wide plank floors do three things narrow floors don't:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Fewer seams across a room.</strong> A 20-foot living room laid in 3" strip has nearly 80 seams. In 8" wide plank it has ~30. The eye reads it as calmer, more spacious.</li>
      <li><strong>Longer visual lines.</strong> Premium European mills produce planks up to 86 inches long. Long planks across an open floor plan create flow rooms can't achieve with shorter pieces.</li>
      <li><strong>Each plank tells more story.</strong> Wider planks show more of the wood's grain character per board — knots, mineral streaks, sawn-face patterns. Each board feels like a piece of wood, not a uniform stripe.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">The Houston humidity problem</h2>
    <p>Wide plank floors are more humidity-sensitive than narrow floors. Simple math: a board that expands 0.5% per humidity unit moves more total inches when it starts at 9" than when it starts at 3". Houston humidity swings from 40% in winter to 90%+ in summer, which is a stress test most other US markets don't impose on flooring.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In <strong>solid hardwood</strong> over Houston slabs, wide plank doesn't really work — it cups, gaps, and fails. Don't do it.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In <strong>engineered hardwood</strong>, wide plank works beautifully because the plywood core resists movement. But you need:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>A stable engineered construction (5/8" or thicker, 4mm+ wear layer, quality core)</li>
      <li>Proper material acclimation (48–72 hours minimum)</li>
      <li>Moisture-tested and properly prepped slab</li>
      <li>Code-correct adhesive and installation</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Skip any of those steps with wide plank and you'll see problems within a year.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Real costs in Houston (2026)</h2>
    <p>Wide plank costs more per square foot than narrow. Rough installed pricing in Houston:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>3"–5" engineered oak:</strong> $14–$18/sq ft installed</li>
      <li><strong>5"–7" wide plank:</strong> $16–$22/sq ft installed</li>
      <li><strong>7"–9" premium wide plank:</strong> $19–$26/sq ft installed</li>
      <li><strong>9"+ extra-wide:</strong> $24–$32+/sq ft installed</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">The jump from 5" to 7" is moderate. The jump from 9" to 12" is steep — and the visual difference isn't proportional.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What we recommend for most Houston homes</h2>
    <p>Our default specification — for River Oaks renovations, Memorial new builds, Heights bungalows, Sugar Land family homes — is <strong>7.5" engineered European white oak, 4mm wear layer, sawn-face, hand-finished</strong>. It's wide enough to look modern, stable enough to handle Houston, and beautiful enough to specify with confidence. Our three core collections — Harbor Cloud, Amber Canyon, Sierra Driftwood — all ship in this format.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">When wider makes sense</h2>
    <p>9"+ wide plank can work in Houston, but only in specific cases:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Very large rooms (the wider planks need scale to look right)</li>
      <li>Modern / minimalist architecture (visual restraint pays off)</li>
      <li>HVAC-controlled, low-humidity-variance interiors</li>
      <li>Owners willing to spend on premium engineered construction</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">If those aren't all true, stay in the 7"–9" range. You'll get 95% of the visual benefit at 70% of the risk.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Bottom line</h2>
    <p>Wide plank hardwood is the right move for most Houston renovations in 2026. Stay in the 7"–9" range, insist on engineered construction, and use an installer who knows our humidity. Done right, wide plank floors look better at year 10 than the day they were installed.</p>

  </article>

